    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1935-03-27T16:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1935-03-27T16:00:00-05:00" n="369"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d369">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">811.5123/2318: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in the United Kingdom</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Bingham</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1935-03-27T16:00:00-05:00"
                            >March 27, 1935—4 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>68. Your telegram 76, February 21, noon [<hi rend="italic">4 p.m.</hi>]. Treasury
                    Department states that under the Revenue Acts of 1932 and 1934 and <pb
                        facs="0588" n="486" xml:id="pg_486"/> Regulations promulgated thereunder
                    British subjects who are nonresident aliens as to the United States and who come
                    here for business purposes are liable for Federal income tax on their income
                    received as compensation for services performed in this country. It is added
                    that while the conclusions set forth appear to be inescapable under existing law
                    consideration is being given to the advisability of recommending to Congress a
                    change which would alleviate the hardships involved.</p>
                <p>A copy of Treasury letter<note n="7" xml:id="d369fn7">Dated March 23, 1935, not
                        printed.</note> is being forwarded by mail.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
